  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison for most money laundering offenses\n- Maximum of 10 years for structuring financial transactions to avoid reporting requirements\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial fines, often up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n- Potential asset forfeiture\n\n3. Additional consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n- Civil penalties\n- Deportation for non-citizens\n\nSpecific penalties can vary based on the specific circumstances, amount of money involved, and whether the offense is part of other criminal activities like drug trafficking or fraud.\n\nThese are general guidelines based on federal statutes, and actual sentencing can depend on individual case details and judicial discretion.",
